message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient presents with vaginal bleeding, emesis, and a tender right suprapubic region, which suggests an ectopic pregnancy. A transvaginal ultrasound at this stage of pregnancy can help identify an intrauterine cystic mass, which is indicative of an ectopic pregnancy. Fetal parts would be more expected in a normal intrauterine pregnancy. Large intramural masses are not commonly seen in early pregnancy, and non-viable fetus would not present with a tender suprapubic region.

Option (B) - intrauterine cystic mass - is the most likely finding in this patient. Fetal parts (A) would be expected in a normal pregnancy, large intramural masses (C) are less likely given the patient's presentation, and non-viable fetus (D) would require confirmation with further testing such as an ultrasound or fetal heart rate monitoring.
